\n{{Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a team classification winners}}\n\n[[Category:UCI WorldTeams|Movistar]]\n[[Category:Cycling teams based in Spain]]\n[[Category:Cycling teams established in 1980]]\n[[Category:Movistar Team (men's team)| ]]\n[[Category:Telef\u00f3nica]]\n[[Category:1980 establishments in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Men's cycling team}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{redirect|Team Caisse d'Epargne|the French banking group|Groupe Caisse d'\u00c9pargne|the Luxembourgish bank|Banque et Caisse d'\u00c9pargne de l'\u00c9tat|the Grand Prix motorcycle racing team sponsored by Movistar|Yamaha Motor Racing}}\n{{Infobox cycling team\n| name         = Movistar Team\n| image        = [[File:Team Movistar logo.png|227px]]\n| code         = MOV\n| registered   = Spain\n| founded      = {{start date|1980}}\n| disbanded    =\n| bicycles     = [[Canyon Bicycles|Canyon]]\n| components   = [[SRAM Corporation|SRAM]]\n| website      = http://www.movistarteam.com/\n| generalmanager      = [[Eusebio Unzu\u00e9]]\n| teammanager  = [[Jos\u00e9 Vicente Garc\u00eda]]<br>[[Pablo Lastras]]<br>[[Jos\u00e9 Luis Jaimerena]]<br>[[Jos\u00e9 Luis Arrieta]]<br>[[Max Sciandri]]\n| discipline   = [[Road bicycle racing|Road]]\n| status       = [[UCI WorldTeam]]\n| season       = 1980\u20131989<br>1990\u20132000<br>2001\u20132003<br>2004\u20132005<br>2005<br />2006<br />2007\u20132010<br />2011\u2013\n| oldname      = Reynolds<br>Banesto<br>iBanesto.com<br>Illes Balears\u2013Banesto<br>Illes Balears\u2013Caisse d'Epargne<br>Caisse d'Epargne\u2013Illes Balears<br>Caisse d'Epargne<br />Movistar Team\n| kitimage     = Team Movistar jersey 2019.jpg\n| current      = 2020 Movistar Team season\n}}\n'''Movistar Team''' ({{UCI code|MOV}}) is a professional [[road bicycle racing]] [[cycling team|team]] which participates at [[UCI WorldTeam]] level and has achieved thirteen [[general classification]] (GC) victories in [[Grand Tours]].  The title sponsor is the Spanish mobile telephone company [[Telef\u00f3nica]], with the team riding under the name of the company's brand ''[[Movistar]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Telefonica to take over as Caisse d'Epargne sponsor from 2011 - Cyclingnews.com |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/telefonica-to-take-over-as-caisse-depargne-sponsor-from-2011 |accessdate=13 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815051537/http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/telefonica-to-take-over-as-caisse-depargne-sponsor-from-2011 |archivedate=15 August 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe team was formed as ''[[Reynolds Metals Company|Reynolds]]'', led by [[\u00c1ngel Arroyo]] and later by [[Pedro Delgado]], who won a [[Tour de France]] and a [[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]], and was subsequently sponsored by ''[[Banesto]]'', under which name the team included 5-time [[Tour de France]] winner [[Miguel Indurain]] and [[Alex Z\u00fclle]], twice winner of the Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a. The team offices are in [[Eg\u00fc\u00e9s]], a [[municipality]] of [[Navarre]], Spain, in the [[metropolitan area]] of [[Pamplona]].<ref>{{cite news |title=2009 Riders and teams Database&nbsp;\u2014 Cyclingnews.com |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/teams/2009/caisse-depargne |accessdate=14 August 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090809104457/http://www.cyclingnews.com/teams/2009/caisse-depargne |archivedate=9 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A later sponsor was [[Groupe Caisse d'Epargne|Caisse d'Epargne]], a French semi-cooperative banking group.\n\nHaving previously used [[Pinarello]] bikes, the team rode Canyon frames in 2014, with [[Campagnolo]] parts. Since 2008, [[Eusebio Unzu\u00e9]] has been the manager of the team after the long running manager, [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Echavarri]], retired from the sport. The [[Directeur sportif|directeurs sportifs]] of the team are [[Jos\u00e9 Vicente Garc\u00eda]], [[Pablo Lastras]], [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Jaimerena]], [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Arrieta]] and [[Max Sciandri]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/sciandri-moves-to-movistar-team-car-in-2019/ |title=Sciandri moves to Movistar team car in 2019 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=11 October 2018 |website=[[cyclingnews.com]]|access-date=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Reynolds (1980\u20131989)===\nThe team began in 1980 as the Reynolds team which Jos\u00e9 Miguel Echavarri as the directeur sportif.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/ploegfiche.php?id=5706|title=Reynolds 1980|publisher=de wielersite.nl|accessdate=21 January 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915102844/http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/ploegfiche.php?id=5706|archivedate=15 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1982 signed a young [[Pedro Delgado]] who acted as a domestique for team leader [[\u00c1ngel Arroyo]] during the [[1982 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pedrodelgado.com/eng/biography/82e.html|title=Biography of Pedro Delgado|publisher=Pedro Delgado.com|accessdate=21 January 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080920005829/http://www.pedrodelgado.com/eng/biography/82e.html|archivedate=20 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Arroyo won the Vuelta after his team controlled the race after he took the lead. But 48 hours after his Vuelta win, the results of a positive test were made known for [[Methylphenidate]] (Ritalin). Arroyo and the Reynolds team denied that Arroyo doped and asked for a B-analysis which confirmed the positive A-sample.  Arroyo became the first winner of the Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a to be disqualified.<ref name=\"lavuelta\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lavuelta.com/05/ingles/historia/82infor.asp?a=1982&s=infor&t=infor&e=1|title=1982 General Information|publisher=La Vuelta.com|accessdate=18 January 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921104459/http://www.lavuelta.com/05/ingles/historia/82infor.asp?a=1982&s=infor&t=infor&e=1|archivedate=21 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Delgado changed teams in 1985 but returned to Reynolds in 1988 where he won the [[1988 Tour de France]] and then the [[1989 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]] with the team. In 1984, [[Miguel Indurain]] made his professional debut with the team.\n\n===Banesto (1990\u20132003)===\nIn 1990, Spanish bank Banesto took over as the main sponsor of the team from Reynolds. Delgado was the team leader for the Tour de France while [[Miguel Indurain]] and [[Juli\u00e1n Gorospe]] were the leaders for the week long stage races. When Gorospe took the lead in that year's Vuelta, the team went behind him in a bid to win the race. However Gorospe lost the leader's jersey and Delgado took over the leadership but could not regain the time that Italian [[Marco Giovannetti]] had gained and ended the race second overall behind Giovannetti. Over the following years, Indurain rose to become a dominator of stage races winning five editions of the Tour de France and two editions of the [[Giro d'Italia]]. Delgado was the team leader for the Vuelta. The team also achieved success with [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Bernard]] who won the 1992 edition of Paris\u2013Nice with the team. The team won the Vuelta again in 1998 with [[Abraham Olano]]. During this time Alex Z\u00fclle joined the team and finished the [[1999 Tour de France]] second overall while legendary climber [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Jim\u00e9nez]] performed in the Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a. The team became known as '''iBanesto.com''' in the final years of the sponsorship of the Banesto bank.\n\n===Illes Balears (2004\u20132005)===\nIn 2004, [[Illes Balears]], the Balearic Island's Tourism Board, became the team's principal sponsor, the team's name was '''Illes Balears-Banesto''' until 2005. Caisse d'Epargne took over from Banesto as the second sponsor in the 2005 season, the team was then known as '''Illes Balears-Caisse d'Epargne'''. Caisse d'Epargne then became the main sponsor in 2006 reversing the  title sponsor ordering with the name, '''Caisse d'Epargne-Illes Balears'''.\n\nThe team fielded a number of strong contenders in the [[2005 Tour de France]] including Francisco Mancebo ([[Spanish National Road Race Championships|former National Champion of Spain]]), [[Alejandro Valverde]], [[Vladimir Karpets]] and sprinter [[Isaac G\u00e1lvez]]. Mancebo produced the best results finishing fourth overall in the General Classification.\n\n===Caisse d'Epargne (2006\u20132010)===\n'''Caisse d'Epargne-Illes Balears''' finished fifth overall (56 minutes, 53 seconds behind [[Team T-Mobile]]) in the Team Classification at the [[2006 Tour de France]]. Individually, the team's top rider, [[\u00d3scar Pereiro]], finished in second place. The Tour victory of [[Phonak (cycling team)|Phonak]] rider [[Floyd Landis]] was almost immediately called into question, after a urine sample taken after his Stage 17 win twice tested positive for banned synthetic [[testosterone (medication)|testosterone]] as well as a ratio of [[testosterone]] to [[epitestosterone]] nearly three times the limit allowed by [[World Anti-Doping Agency]] rules.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/05/sports/05cnd-landis.ready.html|title=Backup Sample on Landis Is Positive|publisher=New York Times|date=5 August 2006|first=Juliet|last=Macur|accessdate=28 April 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506012542/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/05/sports/05cnd-landis.ready.html|archivedate=6 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter hearing of the positive \"A\" test, Pereiro stated that it was only an initial, unconfirmed result and he would not yet consider Landis guilty or himself the Tour winner. \"I have too much respect for Landis to do otherwise\", he said.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/more/specials/tour_de_france/2006/07/27/bc.cyc.tourdefrance.per.ap/index.html|title=Pereiro cautious about Landis case|publisher=SportsIllustrated.com|date=27 July 2006|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090710005529/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/more/specials/tour_de_france/2006/07/27/bc.cyc.tourdefrance.per.ap/index.html|archivedate=10 July 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After hearing that the Landis \"B\" test also came back positive, Pereiro stated that he now considers himself Tour champion and the Landis scandal should not diminish his own achievement. \"Right now I feel like the winner of the Tour de France\", Pereiro said. \"It's a victory for the whole team.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/cycling/5249116.stm|title=I am the Tour champion&nbsp;\u2013 Pereiro|publisher=BBC Sport|date=5 August 2006|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060820111313/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/cycling/5249116.stm|archivedate=20 August 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After nearly two years of appeals, Pereiro was officially upgraded to Tour champion for 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bicycling.com/tourdefrance/article/0,6802,s1-7-123-17423-1,00.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-01-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080803045914/http://www.bicycling.com/tourdefrance/article/0,6802,s1-7-123-17423-1,00.html |archivedate=3 August 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Movistar (2011\u2013 )===\nOn 31 May 2010, the Court of Arbitration for Sport upheld the appeals from WADA and the UCI regarding the suspension of Alejandro Valverde for his implication in the [[Operaci\u00f3n Puerto doping case]]. Valverde was banned for two years, starting 1 January 2010 and after serving the two-year suspension returned to competition in 2012 riding for the Movistar Team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tas-cas.org/en/infogenerales.asp/4-3-4242-1092-4-1-1/5-0-1092-15-1-1/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-05-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605053630/http://www.tas-cas.org/en/infogenerales.asp/4-3-4242-1092-4-1-1/5-0-1092-15-1-1/ |archivedate=5 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/cycling/7790906/Alejandro-Valverde-handed-two-year-ban.html|title=Alejandro Valverde handed two-year ban|author=Telegraph staff|date=31 May 2010|work=Telegraph.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704114035/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/cycling/7790906/Alejandro-Valverde-handed-two-year-ban.html|archivedate=4 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe 2011 season proved to be a transitional one for the team, with their first victory coming as a single stage win in the [[Tour Down Under]], courtesy of [[Francisco Jose Ventoso]]. The team found success with stage wins in the [[Volta a Catalunya]] and [[Tour of the Basque Country]]. The team also won two stages of the [[Giro d'Italia]]: Ventoso won stage 6 and [[Vasil Kiryienka]] won stage 20. The team's final Grand Tour win came courtesy of [[Rui Costa (cyclist)|Rui Costa]] in the [[Tour de France]].\n\nThe 2012 season saw the team re-establish itself as one of the major general classification contenders. The return of Valverde almost immediately brought the team success with a stage win in the Tour Down Under, followed by the overall win of the [[Vuelta a Andaluc\u00eda]] as well as a stage win. Colombian new recruit [[Nairo Quintana]] also brought the team overall victory at the [[Vuelta a Murcia]]. The team scored multiple overall classification victories; Quintana claimed the [[Route du Sud]], Rui Costa the [[Tour de Suisse]], [[Javier Moreno (cyclist)|Javier Moreno]] the [[Vuelta a Castilla y Le\u00f3n]] and finally [[Be\u00f1at Intxausti]] won the  [[Vuelta a Asturias]]. The team also won stages in all three Grand Tours.\n\nThe 2013 season closely followed the previous years, Valverde scored multiple early season results with the [[Trofeo Serra de Tramuntana]] and an overall win in the [[Vuelta a Andaluc\u00eda]]. Quintana further reinforced his potential as a Grand Tour GC rider with the overall win in the Tour of the Basque Country as well as claiming second place in the [[2013 Tour de France|Tour de France]], taking the King of the Mountains in addition to the Young rider classification. He further reinforced his reputation as a force to be reckoned with, with an overall win in the [[Vuelta a Burgos]]. Intxausti got the team's final overall win of the year and Costa won the UCI World Road Race championships. For the 2014 season the team confirmed that they would shift from [[Pinarello]] bikes to [[Canyon Bicycles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/movistar-to-ride-canyon-in-2014|title=Movistar to ride Canyon in 2014|author=Cycling News|work=Cyclingnews.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141015084129/http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/movistar-to-ride-canyon-in-2014|archivedate=15 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFor 2014, the team adopted a 'divide and conquer' based tactic for the season's Grand Tours; first sending Quintana to the Giro, Valverde to the Tour and then finally both riders to the Vuelta. Quintana achieved the team's first victory - winning stage 4 of the [[Tour de San Luis]] as well as the overall classification, [[Adriano Malori]] also won the individual time trial stage. Once again Valverde won the Vuelta a Andaluc\u00eda as well as the Vuelta a Murcia, [[Roma Maxima]], [[GP Miguel Indurain]] and [[La Fl\u00e8che Wallonne]]. In May, Quintana won the team's first Grand Tour since Valverde's 2009 Vuelta victory, the [[2014 Giro d'Italia]]. As with the previous season, Quintana defended his Vuelta a Burgos title winning it for the second straight year.\n\nIn August 2014, the team announced the signing of [[Marc Soler]] ({{ct|LIZ|2014b}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/movistar-announce-signing-of-marc-soler|title=Movistar announce signing of Marc Soler|author=Cycling News|work=Cyclingnews.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826113339/http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/movistar-announce-signing-of-marc-soler|archivedate=26 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Rub\u00e9n Fern\u00e1ndez (cyclist)|Rub\u00e9n Fern\u00e1ndez]] ({{ct|CJR}}) on a 2-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rub\u00e9n Fern\u00e1ndez signs for Movistar - Cyclingnews.com|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/ruben-fernandez-signs-for-movistar|accessdate=8 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826115324/http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/ruben-fernandez-signs-for-movistar|archivedate=26 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2015 Tour de France]], the team finished first in the teams classification, and the two top men of the team, Nairo Quintana and Alejandro Valverde finished second and third in the general classification, respectively, with Quintana also winning the white jersey as best young rider, and finishing second in the king of the mountains classification.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://espn.go.com/sports/endurance/story/_/id/13321787/endurance-sports-velonews-nairo-quintana-comes-just-short-tour-de-france |title= Lost time in Stage 2 will haunt Nairo Quintana |author= Andrew Hood |date= 26 July 2015 |work= VeloNews.com |publisher= ESPN |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150729051926/http://espn.go.com/sports/endurance/story/_/id/13321787/endurance-sports-velonews-nairo-quintana-comes-just-short-tour-de-france |archivedate= 29 July 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.bicycling.com/racing/2015-tour-de-france/stage-20-analysis-quintana-and-froomes-battle-what-ifs |title= Stage 20 Analysis: Quintana and Froome's Battle of What Ifs |author= Joe Lindsey |date= 25 July 2015 |publisher= Bicycling.com |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150726221621/http://www.bicycling.com/racing/2015-tour-de-france/stage-20-analysis-quintana-and-froomes-battle-what-ifs |archivedate= 26 July 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2016 [[2016 Tour de France|Tour]], the team finished first in the teams classification by 8' 14\" over Team Sky. Nairo Quintana made the podium by finishing third overall in the general classification standings and Ion Izagirre claimed victory on stage 20. Later during the [[2016 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]], Quintana won stage 10 and the overall. The team concluded the year with their fourth win in the team ranking of [[2016 UCI World Tour]].\n\nIn 2019, [[Richard Carapaz]] won the [[2019 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]], and the team won the team classification in all three Grand Tours. The team's season is captured in a documentary series, [[The Least Expected Day: Inside the Movistar Team 2019]], available on [[Netflix]].\n\n==Team roster==\n{{Updated|2 January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movistarteam.com/en/2019-12-19/2020-launch|title=Movistar Team ready to open new era in 2020|work={{ct|MOV|2020|nolink=yes}}|publisher=Abarca Sports SL|date=19 December 2019|accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>}}\n{{Cycling squad start}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Juan Diego Alba]]|nat=COL|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1997|9|11}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Jorge Arcas]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|7|8}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Carlos Betancur]]|nat=COL|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1989|10|13}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[H\u00e9ctor Carretero]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1995|5|28}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Dario Cataldo]]|nat=ITA|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1985|3|17}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Gabriel Cullaigh]]|nat=GBR|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1996|4|8}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[I\u00f1igo Elosegui]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1998|3|6}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Imanol Erviti]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|11|15}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Juri Hollmann]]|nat=GER|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1999|8|30}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Johan Jacobs]]|nat=SUI|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1997|3|1}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Matteo Jorgenson]]|nat=USA|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1999|7|1}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Enric Mas]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1995|1|7}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Llu\u00eds Mas]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1989|10|15}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Sebasti\u00e1n Mora]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|2|19}}}}\n{{Cycling squad mid}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Mathias Norsgaard]]|nat=DEN|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1997|5|5}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Nelson Oliveira]]|nat=POR|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1989|3|6}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Antonio Pedrero]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1991|10|23}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Eduard Prades]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1987|8|9}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[J\u00fcrgen Roelandts]]|nat=BEL|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1985|7|2}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Jos\u00e9 Joaqu\u00edn Rojas]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1985|6|8}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Einer Rubio]]|nat=COL|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1998|2|22}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Sergio Samitier]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1995|8|31}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Eduardo Sep\u00falveda]]|nat=ARG|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1991|6|13}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Marc Soler]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1993|11|22}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Albert Torres]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|4|26}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Alejandro Valverde]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1980|4|25}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Carlos Verona]]|nat=ESP|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|11|4}}}}\n{{Cycling squad rider|name=[[Davide Villella]]|nat=ITA|birthdate={{birth date and age|df=yes|1991|6|27}}}}\n{{Cycling squad end}}\n\n==Major wins==\n{{main|List of wins by Reynolds and its successors}}\n\n==National, continental and world champions==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;1982\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Lagu\u00eda]]\n;1983\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race  [[Carlos Hern\u00e1ndez (cyclist)|Carlos Hern\u00e1ndez]]\n;1992\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race  [[Miguel Indurain]]\n;1995\n:[[File:MaillotMundialCrono.PNG|20px]] World Time Trial [[Miguel Indurain]]\n;1997\n:[[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] British Road Race [[Jeremy Hunt (cyclist)|Jeremy Hunt]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race  [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Jim\u00e9nez]]\n;1998\n:[[File:MaillotMundialCrono.PNG|20px]] World Time Trial [[Abraham Olano]]\n;2003\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race  [[Rub\u00e9n Plaza]]\n;2004\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race  [[Francisco Mancebo]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Time Trial [[Jose Ivan Gutierrez]]\n;2005\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Time Trial [[Jose Ivan Gutierrez]]\n;2006\n:[[File:MaillotFra.PNG|20px]] France Road Race [[Florent Brard]]\n;2007\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Joaquim Rodr\u00edguez]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Time Trial [[Jose Ivan Gutierrez]]\n;2008\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Alejandro Valverde]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Time Trial [[Luis Le\u00f3n Sanchez]]\n;2010\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Jose Ivan Gutierrez]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Time Trial [[Luis Le\u00f3n Sanchez]]\n:[[File:MaillotPortugal.PNG|20px]] Portugal Time Trial [[Rui Costa (cyclist)|Rui Costa]]\n;2011\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Jose Joaquin Rojas]]\n;2012\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Francisco Ventoso]]\n:[[File:MaillotBielorrusia.PNG|20px]] Belarus Time Trial [[Branislau Samoilau]]\n;2013\n:[[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] British Time Trial [[Alex Dowsett]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Time Trial [[Jonathan Castroviejo]]\n:[[File:MaillotPortugal.PNG|20px]] Portugal Time Trial [[Rui Costa (cyclist)|Rui Costa]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Jes\u00fas Herrada]]\n:[[File:MaillotMundial.PNG|20px]] World Road Race [[Rui Costa (cyclist)|Rui Costa]]\n;2014\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Time Trial [[Alejandro Valverde]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Ion Izagirre]]\n:[[File:MaillotItalia.svg|20px]] Italy Time Trial [[Adriano Malori]]\n;2015\n:[[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] British Time Trial [[Alex Dowsett]]\n:[[File:MaillotItalia.svg|20px]] Italy Time Trial [[Adriano Malori]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Time Trial [[Jonathan Castroviejo]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Alejandro Valverde]]\n;2016\n:[[File:MaillotReinoUnido.PNG|20px]] British Time Trial [[Alex Dowsett]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Time Trial [[Ion Izagirre]]\n:[[File:MaillotPortugal.PNG|20px]] Portugal Time Trial [[Nelson Oliveira]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Jos\u00e9 Joaqu\u00edn Rojas]]\n:[[File:UEC Champion Jersey.svg|20px]] European Time Trial [[Jonathan Castroviejo]]\n;2017\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Time Trial [[Jonathan Castroviejo]]\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Jes\u00fas Herrada]]\n;2018\n:[[File:MaillotMundial.PNG|20px]] World Road Race [[Alejandro Valverde]]\n;2019\n:[[File:MaillotEspa\u00f1a.PNG|20px]] Spain Road Race [[Alejandro Valverde]]\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Former riders==\n{{main|List of former Movistar riders}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{ct|MOT2}}\n*[[List of cycling teams in Spain]]\n\n==References==\n{